nodes.name: AccommodationFacility
nodes.label: Accommodation facility
nodes.description: A building or collection of buildings without a singular purpose, but generally used for accommodation.

nodes.name: Action
nodes.label: Action
nodes.description: An activity, or the occurrence of an activity, that may utilise resources and may be focused against an objective.

nodes.name: Actor
nodes.label: Actor
nodes.description: Base actor category

nodes.name: Aircraft
nodes.label: Aircraft
nodes.description: A Vehicle that is designed to fly within the earth's atmosphere.

nodes.name: Airfield
nodes.label: Airfield
nodes.description: An area prepared for the accommodation (including buildings and installations) or equipment of landing and take-off of aircraft.

nodes.name: Anchorage
nodes.label: Anchorage
nodes.description: A place where a vessel may anchor, usually designated in charts, offering suitable holding ground and shelter.

nodes.name: Apron
nodes.label: Apron
nodes.description: A defined area on a land aerodrome intended to accommodate aircraft for the purposes of loading or unloading passengers, mail or cargo, fuelling, parking or maintenance.

nodes.name: Bank

nodes.description: An establishment where money is stored for saving or commercial purposes.

nodes.name: Barracks
nodes.label: Barracks
nodes.description: Military accommodation facility for personnel and unit support.

nodes.name: Basin
nodes.label: Basin
nodes.description: A partially enclosed, man-made or improved water area providing safe anchorage and berthing for vessels.

nodes.name: Berth
nodes.label: Berth
nodes.description: A designated location in a port or harbour where a vessel may be moored, usually alongside a quay, pier, or jetty.

nodes.name: Bivouac
nodes.label: Bivouac
nodes.description: Temporary encampment area for troops in the field.

nodes.name: Civilian
nodes.label: Civilian
nodes.description: A person who is not a member of the armed forces or other organized armed groups; generally protected from direct attack under the law of armed conflict.

nodes.name: Cropland
nodes.label: cropland
nodes.description: An area that has been tilled for the planting of crops.

nodes.name: Cryosphere
nodes.label: Cryosphere
nodes.description: Snow and ice environments (glaciers, pack ice, snowfields) that constrain movement, logistics, and signatures.

nodes.name: Ditch
nodes.label: Ditch
nodes.description: Linear excavation used as a military obstacle.

nodes.name: Equipment
nodes.label: Equipment
nodes.description: Materiel that is neither intended for consumption nor an unexploded piece of ordnance.

nodes.name: Facility
nodes.label: Facility
nodes.description: Base facility category

nodes.name: Facsimile
nodes.label: Facsimile
nodes.description: A service provided by means of electronic scanning of a document, transmitting it as data by telecommunications links, and producing an exact copy at the receiver.

nodes.name: Farm
nodes.label: farm
nodes.description: A tract of land, including buildings and structures, whose primary use is the production of food (for example: crops or livestock).

nodes.name: Ford
nodes.label: Ford
nodes.description: A shallow place in a river or stream allowing one to walk or drive across.

nodes.name: Fortification
nodes.label: Fortification
nodes.description: Military defensive works designed to strengthen a position against attack.

nodes.name: Harbour
nodes.label: Harbour
nodes.description: A sheltered area of water where ships, boats, and barges can be moored safely, often with port facilities.

nodes.name: Helipad
nodes.label: Helipad
nodes.description: A small, designated area (usually with a prepared surface) used for the take-off, landing, or parking of helicopters.

nodes.name: Heliport
nodes.label: Heliport
nodes.description: An aerodrome or defined area on a structure intended or used for the arrival, departure, and surface movement of helicopters.

nodes.name: Image
nodes.label: Image
nodes.description: An imagery product.

nodes.name: Jetty
nodes.label: Jetty
nodes.description: A structure projecting from the shore into a body of water to influence current or tide or to protect a harbour; also used for mooring vessels.

nodes.name: Lighthouse
nodes.label: Lighthouse
nodes.description: A tower or other structure with a powerful light that gives a continuous or intermittent signal to navigators.

nodes.name: Lock
nodes.label: Lock
nodes.description: An enclosed section of waterway with gates at each end, by which the level of water can be altered to raise or lower vessels as they pass through.

nodes.name: Market
nodes.label: Market
nodes.description: A facility where commercial activity is conducted and goods and services are bought and sold.

nodes.name: Materiel
nodes.label: Materiel
nodes.description: An apparatus, equipment or supply of military interest without distinction as to its application for administrative or combat purposes.

nodes.name: Military
nodes.label: Military
nodes.description: A person who serves in the regular armed forces of a state, subject to military law and organization.

nodes.name: Minefield
nodes.label: Minefield
nodes.description: Area seeded with land or sea mines as an obstacle.

nodes.name: Object
nodes.label: Object
nodes.description: An individually identified object that has military or civilian significance.

nodes.name: Office
nodes.label: Office
nodes.description: A place in which business, professional or clerical activities are conducted.

nodes.name: Orchard
nodes.label: orchard
nodes.description: A tract covered by systematic plantings of trees that yield fruits (including nuts).

nodes.name: Organisation
nodes.label: Organisation
nodes.description: An administrative or functional structure.

nodes.name: Paramilitary
nodes.label: Paramilitary
nodes.description: A person who belongs to a non-regular armed organization with military structure or functions (e.g., militias, gendarmerie, irregular forces), typically outside the standing armed forces.

nodes.name: Person
nodes.label: Person
nodes.description: A human being of military or civilian significance.

nodes.name: Pier
nodes.label: Pier
nodes.description: A platform supported on pillars or girders leading out from the shore into a body of water, used as a landing stage for boats.

nodes.name: Port
nodes.label: Port
nodes.description: A town or city with a harbour where ships load or unload, especially one where customs officers are stationed.

nodes.name: Quay
nodes.label: Quay
nodes.description: A solidly constructed platform, usually parallel to the shore, where a vessel can be loaded or unloaded on one side of the vessel only.

nodes.name: Railway
nodes.label: Railway
nodes.description: A permanent track composed of a line of parallel metal rails fixed to sleepers, for transport of passengers and goods in trains.

nodes.name: Road
nodes.label: Road
nodes.description: A wide way leading from one place to another, especially one with a specially prepared surface which vehicles can use.

nodes.name: Runway
nodes.label: Runway
nodes.description: A defined rectangular area on a land aerodrome prepared for the landing and take-off of aircraft.

nodes.name: Sensor
nodes.label: Sensor
nodes.description: A device that detects or measures a physical property and records, indicates, or otherwise responds to it.

nodes.name: Shop
nodes.label: Shop
nodes.description: A small retail store or a speciality department in a large store.

nodes.name: Slipway
nodes.label: Slipway
nodes.description: The prepared and usually reinforced inclined plane upon which the keel blocks are laid for supporting a vessel under construction.

nodes.name: Spacecraft
nodes.label: Spacecraft
nodes.description: A Vehicle that is capable of operating beyond the earth's atmosphere.

nodes.name: Tool
nodes.comment: An instrument with which some operation is performed; a means of effecting something.
nodes.label: Tool

nodes.name: Trail
nodes.label: Trail
nodes.description: A beaten path or track through rough country such as a forest or moor, used for travel or transport on foot, horseback, or by vehicle.

nodes.name: Tunnel
nodes.label: Tunnel
nodes.description: An underground or underwater passage dug through the surrounding soil/earth/rock and enclosed except for entry and exit, commonly used for road and rail traffic.

nodes.name: Unit
nodes.label: Unit
nodes.description: A MilitaryOrganisation whose structure is prescribed by competent authority.

nodes.name: Vehicle
nodes.label: Vehicle
nodes.description: A conveyance for transporting persons or things.

nodes.name: Vessel
nodes.label: Vessel
nodes.description: A Vehicle that is designed to operate on or under the water surface.

nodes.name: Weapon
nodes.label: Weapon
nodes.description: Equipment of any kind used in warfare or combat to attack and overcome an enemy.

nodes.name: Wetland
nodes.label: Wetland
nodes.description: Areas with water-saturated soils (marshes, swamps, bogs) that significantly affect maneuver, concealment, and engineering tasks.

nodes.name: Application
nodes.comment: Application represents a specific instance of a software program running on a device. Running processes are considered to be members of this class. At rest applications are considered to be members of the Data class with Data Type Code.
nodes.label: Application

nodes.name: CyberDEM
nodes.comment: The multiplicity of an attribute is expressed in the form datatype[min..max], where the  default number is assumed to be [1..1] similarly to XML, min=1 and max=1 if not specified (UML)

nodes.name: Data
nodes.comment: Data represents information encapsulated in an instance or collection of file(s), message(s), or record(s) in a database. Data can represent a specific information object or a kind of information, e.g. a specific tactical message or messages that contain SPOTREP information. CyberObject.Name is the filename, subject, information kind, etc. At rest applications are considered to be members of this class with Data Type Code. Running processes are considered to be members of the Application class.
nodes.label: Data

nodes.name: Degrade
nodes.comment: Degrade represets denying access to, or operation of, a target to a level represented as a percentage of capacity. [JP3-12]
nodes.label: Degrade

nodes.name: Deny
nodes.comment: Deny represents preventing access to, operation of, or availability of a target function by a specified level for a specified time, by degrade, disrupt, or destroy. Deny is an abstract class intended as an organizational construct; specific effects are instantiated as subclasses.
nodes.label: Deny

nodes.name: Destroy
nodes.comment: Destroy represents completely and irreparably denying access to, or operation of, a target. [JP3-12] Destroy is an abstract class intended as an organizational construct; specific effects are instantiated as subclasses.
nodes.label: Destroy

nodes.name: Detect
nodes.comment: Detect represents discovering or discerning the existence, presence, or fact of an intrusion into information systems. [ATT&CK v13]
nodes.label: Detect

nodes.name: Device
nodes.comment: Device represents an electronic device capable of operating in cyberspace.
nodes.label: Device

nodes.name: Disrupt
nodes.comment: Disrupt represents completely but temporarily denying access to, or operation of, a target for a period of time. [JP3-12] Disrupt is an abstract class intended as an organizational construct; specific effects are instantiated as subclasses.
nodes.label: Disrupt

nodes.name: Enumerations
nodes.comment: The following are the Cyber DEM enumerations at the time the standard was completed. Updates to the enumeration values may occur between versions of the standard via the Enumerations SWG. See the latest version of SISO-REF-010 for the current values.

nodes.name: KeyValuePair
nodes.comment: Key Value Pairs are for specifying additional criteria for targets and Detect Acquired Information.

nodes.name: Manipulate
nodes.comment: Manipulate represents the effect of controlling or changing information, information systems, and/or networks to create physical denial effects, using deception, decoying, conditioning, spoofing, falsification, and other similar techniques. nodes.label: Manipulate

nodes.name: MitreID

nodes.name: Network
nodes.comment: Network represents a data network including LANs, WANs, tactical radio data networks, cellular data networks, etc.; networks can be composed of other networks, e.g. a WAN is a collection of LANs. CyberObject.Name is the domain name or subnet address range.

nodes.name: NetworkInterfaceStruct
nodes.comment: Network Interface Struct represents a network interface, hardware and/or software, that enables a device to connect to a network link. A network interface can exist with or without a link, but not without a device.

nodes.name: Persona

nodes.name: RelatedObjectStruct
nodes.comment: Related Object Struct describes properties about a relationship between objects.

nodes.name: Service
nodes.comment: Service represents an application that provides a service to network clients.

nodes.name: System

nodes.name: Capability_CyberOffensive

nodes.name: Capability_CyberSupportCoordination

nodes.name: Capability_Engineering
nodes.label: Engineering capability
nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the ability to perform construction or destruction activities. This includes performing mobility and counter-mobility tasks. 

Remarks:

EngineeringCapability provides additional information concerning the conditions for which the engineering capability is defined, that is, the type of facility which is being constructed or destroyed (or in the case of obstacles, breached) as well as the dimensions of that facility. Engineering capabilities can be described for different echelon levels. For instance, a bridge-building platoon may be capable of either constructing two bridges, each 20 metres long, or a single bridge that is 40 metres long. A company that is made up of three platoons may therefore be capable of building a single bridge that is 120 metres long. The first capability can be described at platoon level, the second at company level.

nodes.name: Capability_Fire
nodes.label: Fire capability
nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Facilities, Equipment, Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the ability to discharge or launch a projectile or missile. 

Remarks:

FireCapability provides additional information about the type of projectile, which is being discharged or launched.

nodes.name: Capability_Handling
nodes.label: Handling capability
nodes.description: A Capability, required for planning, of those Facilities and Equipment that are deemed as having the ability to move Materiel (raw materials, scrap, semi-finished, and finished) to, through, and from productive processes; in warehouses and storage; and in receiving and shipping areas.

nodes.name: Capability_Maintenance
nodes.label: Maintenance capability
nodes.description: A Capability, required for planning, of those Facilities, Equipment, Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the ability to provide a range of activities required to restore or maintain operational usage.

nodes.name: Capability_Mobility
nodes.label: Mobility capability
nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Facilities, Materiel, Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the nominal ability to move in space, air, on water, under water, or over a specific type of terrain. 

Remarks:

MobilityCapability specifies additional information about the kind of mobility and, in certain cases, the conditions for which the manoeuvre capability is defined, in particular, the type of terrain that is being traversed.

nodes.name: Capability_Operational

nodes.name: CyberAttack
nodes.comment: Techniques represent how an adversary achieves a tactical goal by performing an action. Sub-techniques are a more specific description of the adversarial behavior used to achieve a goal. They describe behavior at a lower level than a technique. Techniques are identified by “T####” and sub-techniques are indicated by the “.###” notation. [ATT&CK v13]
nodes.label: Cyber attack

nodes.name: CyberDefend
nodes.comment:
Cyber Defend is a cyberspace action taken within protected cyberspace to defeat specific threats that have breached or are threatening to breach the cyberspace security measures and include actions to detect, characterize, counter, and mitigate threats, including malware or the unauthorized activities of users, and to restore the system to a secure configuration. [JP3-12]
Mitigations represent security concepts and classes of technologies that can be used to prevent a technique or sub-technique from being successfully executed. Mitigations are identified by “M####” notation. [ATT&CK v13]
nodes.label: Cyber defend

nodes.name: CyberEffect
nodes.comment: A Cyber Effect is a change, in or through cyberspace, which is a result or consequence of an action or other cause. [Lexico, adapted] Cyber Effect is an abstract class intended as an organizational construct; specific effects are instantiated as subclasses. Cyber Effect is further decomposed into deny (degrade, destroy, and disrupt) and manipulate consistent with US Joint Publication 3-12 [JP3-12] and detect.
nodes.label: Cyber effect

nodes.comment: represent non-persistent cyber actions and effects as opposed to persistent cyber objects.

The content of the orders is represented in the Target Modifiers.

CyberEvent.Target identifies the data being exfiltrated. CyberEvent.ActorID identifies the actor performing the exfiltration.
